data.content:
**In .NET 11, all your synchronous Cosmos DB calls will throw at runtime — with no opt-in to restore them.**

In EF Core 10, sync I/O on the Cosmos provider was unsupported by default but you could re-enable it. **EF Core 11 removes that opt-in entirely.** Every sync call (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()`) always throws.

**Fix — convert to async:**

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

You'll also need to propagate `async`/`await` up through all callers of these methods. Remove any `.EnableSyncOverAsync()` or similar opt-in configuration — it no longer has any effect.
